The Beck family, three generations strong, set out to harvest oysters from managed reserves after years of waiting for them to grow to legal size.
Meanwhile, environmentalists are pushing for stricter regulations on nitrogen pollution from sewage plants to protect the Chesapeake Bay.
Efforts to eradicate nutria have restored marshlands, but concerns remain about introducing Asian oysters.
Despite slow progress, officials are determined to meet cleanup goals by 2010.
The Chesapeake Bay remains a focal point for conservation efforts and sustainable fisheries management, with ongoing debates over the future of oyster farming and environmental preservation.
